At some point I noticed that when I click on a `<button>` in my component that has an event handler attached, it causes the re-render of my component, wiping its internal state. After some googling I found that this is an intended behaviour, and to opt out we need to implement an `IHandleEvent` in the component. 
I found and precisely followed [these docs](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/aspnet/core/blazor/performance?view=aspnetcore-5.0&pivots=server#avoid-rerendering-after-handling-events-without-state-changes-1) that describe how to do it, however whatever I do, my button still refreshes the state of a component. I've spent a couple of days trying to troubleshoot this, but I believe I'm missing something very simple, so I though I'd ask for help.

Below is the code of my component:
```razor
@implements IHandleEvent

<div class="form-group">
    <input type="text" class="form-control" value="@Output">
    <button @onclick="Clear" class="btn btn-sm btn-outline-dark">Clear</button>
</div>

@code {
    private async Task Clear()
    {
        var a = 2 + 2;
    }

    private object output;
    [Parameter]
    public object Output
    {
        get => output;
        set
        {
            if (output?.ToString() == value.ToString()) return;
            output = value.ToString();
        }
    }

    Task IHandleEvent.HandleEventAsync(EventCallbackWorkItem callback, object arg) => callback.InvokeAsync(arg);
}
```

The value for the input comes from the parent component.

---

The test I do is very simple:
- I modify the internal state of the input component, add some characters inside
- then I click the button to execute `2+2`
- immediately after that my component is refreshed and the characters from step 1 disappear, leaving me with its initial state that comes from the parent

![Animation](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/2878904/144108012-bcfd2d72-1524-4073-8c2d-4cae2481e215.gif)

I don't think the docs are incorrect, as someone would have reported it by now, so what am I doing wrong?

